{"cursor":"30269","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"In thermodynamics, a thermodynamic system is in 'thermodynamic equilibrium' when\nit is in thermal equilibrium, mechanical equilibrium, radiative equilibrium, and\nchemical equilibrium. Equilibrium means a state of balance. In a state of\nthermodynamic equilibrium, there are no net flows of matter or of energy, no\nphase changes, and no unbalanced potentials (or driving forces), within the\nsystem. A system that is in thermodynamic equilibrium experiences no changes\nwhen it is isolated from its surroundings.\n\nIn non-equilibrium systems there are net flows of matter or energy, or phase\nchanges are occurring; if such changes can be triggered to occur in a system in\nwhich they are not already occurring, it is said to be in a metastable\nequilibrium.\n","linknr":429,"url":"Thermodynamic_equilibrium","recorded":1362375203,"links":42,"instances":["mathematician"],"pdf":["http://ads.harvard.edu/books/1989fsa..book/AbookC15.pdf"],"categories":["Equilibrium chemistry","Thermodynamics"],"headings":["Overview","Local and global equilibrium","Types of equilibrium","General references","References","Cited bibliography","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/22/Carnot_heat_engine_2.svg/220px-Carnot_heat_engine_2.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/3/5/4/354c808b3ac7ff5bd75faa26bcc36220.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/b/9/e/b9ece18c950afbfa6b0fdbfa4ff731d3.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/d/e/7/de71b72c4f62f20d117414dd2f33ca25.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/8/d/9/8d9c307cb7f3c4a32822a51922d1ceaa.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/a/f/7/af7e8a85df47250ffab736b7a8807488.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/2/a/e/2aede3b55c027fe4392429d6474ec397.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/c/4/c/c4ca4238a0b923820dcc509a6f75849b.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/8/8/8/888fa252e9cde41ef196d5154cd7219c.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/5/2/0/5206560a306a2e085a437fd258eb57ce.png","//u